uild of Commerce</span><hr size=1> Two things I enjoy about Everquest are:<br>
1.  Meeting and grouping with others for hunting, camps, and raids.<br>
2.  Acquiring and upgrading equipment to make #1 more feasible through trade and negotiation.<br>
<br>
Statement:  The numerous Guilds address #1 quite thoroughly and to a large extent #2 as well.<br>
<br>
Question:  Has there ever been a Guild established that concentrates on Commerce as it's first Goal?<br>
<br>
Problem:  Trades, whether for money or other, take place in every zone in the world of Norrath.  But because of the complexities of the world sometimes finding a Buyer or Seller can be arduous.  Broadcast auctions are limited to the zone of the Seller or Buyer.  Traveling to the Tunnel in E.C. can be relatively expensive and/or time consuming.  Further, once you arrive, there is no guarantee you can find a Buyer or Seller.<br>
<br>
Solution:  A group of PCs, a Commerce Guild if you will, could organize and assign players to cover certain zones in an effort to connect Buyers and Sellers.  These agents could take consignments from other PCs to help them find a market.  A PC could place an order to sell or buy a certain item with the Guild.  The Zone Agent would send this order to the Pit Boss in E.C.  The Pit Boss would broadcast the order out to other members of the Guild throughout the entire world.  When another Agent finds a matching Customer for the Broadcasted item said Agent would notify the Pit Boss.  The Pit Boss would communicate with both Agents to negotiate a price or instruct Agents to tell the PCs the names of interested parties.  Of course this would cost both the Buyer and the Seller a fee.  5% on items 100pp or over?  Delivery is up to the PCs involved.  Once the names are exchanged the Guild has completed it's service.<br>
<br>
Who wins?:<br>
Seller: Finds a quick market<br>
Buyer: Finds the item they want quickly<br>
Seller's Agent: Makes 5% from Seller<br>
Buyer's Agent: Makes 5% from Buyer<br>
Pit Boss:  Earns a commission directly from the Guild as a percent of the days activity he conducted.<br>
Guild:  Membership is free.  But active members must pay a fee to the Guild based upon their activity payable once a week.  50% of paid commissions?<br>
<br>
Why this might work:<br>
1.  Guild could advertise their connections by Auction.  Example: &quot;Commerce Guild now taking Buy or Sell orders in 40 zones&quot;.  I think most PCs would like the idea of this network when trying to sell or buy expensive items.  If a PC is looking to pay 10K for a FBSS then he probably won't be grudge a 500pp commission if he is matched with a Seller in a matter of minutes.  (lol, maybe he would).<br>
2.  Anyone could become an Agent.  No minimum level to join is required.  Level 1 PCs can excel at this as much as Level 50 PCs.  No upfront fee to join.  Only pay as you play and complete transactions.<br>
3.  Zones assigned first come first serve.  The Pitt boss would assign certain zones to agents based on first come first serve.  If an Agent logs on at 2:00pm and the Butcher Block zone is open then that agent gets the assignment and maybe one open adjacent zone if the agent has time to handle 2.  Pitt Boss can keep a waiting list for active players requesting particular zones.  One agent leaves, then the Agent at the top of the list gets the zone.<br>
4.  Factor while you do other things:  This would not require a 100% of the Agent's attention.  They can fight, camp, and raid while assigned to a zone.  They simply need to note Pit Boss orders and occasionally send out an Auction message for Order Taking or Order Offering.  Just keep your eyes open for potential business.<br>
5.  Income:  Do the numbers.  If an agent brokers five deals in one week worth a total of 20kpp then he makes 1000pp in commissions less 500pp in Guild Membership fees.  Thats 500pp for just typing.  If a Pit Boss brokers 20kpp in one weeks worth of transactions then he might get 2.5% or 500pp.   The rest would go to Guild Officers and a General Fund.<br>
<br>
Of course there are many problems with this but I have other ideas to make this work.  I am interested to know if anyone else would like to explore this possibility with me.<br>
<br>
Thanks, Roddingham<br>
