<br>
I have read your post on the economy and agree that PCs should be able to make the best equipment.  That with item degrade (of some type) might be an improvement to the economy.<br>
<br>
Responding to your post in order:<br>
<br>
1.“I think each broker should set his own commission rate or perhaps set a payment to owner price”.  <br>
<br>
This is an excellent idea and the guild should or would probably evolve into this anyway.  But, to start out I think it should be as easy as possible.  Commission rate should be standard so customers don’t resent the Guild and refuse to use us because we don’t provide an equitable service regardless of Agent or Zone.  Same goes for a set payment which has the additional problem of the actual exchange of the items in question.  If the deal you arrange is too sweet then the Buyer and Seller may get very unhappy if they talk during the exchange and find out that you made 50% on the deal.  Of course you could just buy the item from the seller once you find a Buyer but that would require a lot of start up capital.<br>
<br>
2.“Guild fees seem steep”.  <br>
<br>
It is all relative.  Would you rather have 500pp after paying 500pp in fees or would you rather have nothing.  The strength of the Guild would be the network.  This requires coordination, which costs time and money.  The Guild is offering its agents a connected network of markets around the world.  All you have to do is type, negotiate price, and provide the connection.  You don’t have to sit still or travel abroad.  It would be cake.  Also, I was just throwing out a number on the fees.<br>
<br>
3.“Guild fees go towards what exactly”.  <br>
<br>
This system requires several key personnel to make it work.  The Pit Boss must be organized and cannot do anything else while on duty.  He must keep a record of all Buy Orders, Sell Orders, and completed transactions detailed by agent and amount.  The Pit Boss is the centerpiece otherwise you would have 50 agents in the field working their own list in a global manner that would lead to spammed guild speak and lose of control.  Before logging off the Pit Boss would submit his records to a V.P. of Operations in charge of coordinating successive Pit Bosses as well as recruiting new Agents.  You would need a CFO who would use the records to calculate fees and commissions.  The CFO would also be in charge of collecting the fees and distributing the commissions (think Druid with port and sow). There would be more needed of course but all these people would need to be paid for their service.   Salaries would be public notice and majority approved by Senior members.  The rest would go to a fund that could be used as the Guild wishes (finance a library of uber equipment that could be checked out by Guild members for raids).  I am not trying to make anyone a millionaire.  As far as enforcing commissions goes, the only punishment you can dole out for fee avoidance would be de-guilding.  I am sure some will be dishonest in the short run but if you are a long run thinker then you will realize the future potential of good membership with the Guild.<br>
<br>
Addressing your ideas:<br>
1.“Guild set up to promote business”.  Obviously I agree.<br>
2.I agree with everything stated about membership, ethics, and reputation.<br>
3.I agree, membership should not be limited to Mains.<br>
4.“No fees for belonging to the guild exists as the guild has no costs associated with it”.  O.k., here I disagree for the reasons stated above.  But in general, no cost to join. Pay as you complete deals.  This would not be that hard for Agents.  Keep your eyes open, send out orders over the auction, negotiate when needed, and pay your fees once a week.<br>
5.“No price wars between members”.  With a standard commission this would be a none issue.<br>
6.“Changes must be ratified by 2/3 majority” No problem there.<br>
<br>
The main thing I was considering when formulating this was “how easy could you make it for agents in the field”?  This is pretty simple yet could be very profitable to anyone, any level.  Sure, the details at the top would require work, coordination, and RL communication but it would also be a lot of fun (if you enjoy this sort of thing). <br>
<br>
Herder, again, thanks for responding.  If you like, we could exchange Phone numbers and discuss it more in depth.  I would appreciate anyone’s comments or suggestions.<br>
<br>
Thanks,<br>
Roddingham <br>
<br>
P.S. All of the above was stated using my original train of thought.<br>
<br>
Second thoughts:  Herder, you could be right or at least more right than me.  A simple system of agents charging their own commissions for helping to make a connection on one end would be far easier.  No fees. No pit bosses. No VP of Op, No CFO, and no whatever else.  It would literally be a group of people using Guild speak to buy and sell things on a Global scale.  I know most Guilds already do this to an extent but we could be known as the Guide to contact when you need something bought or sold fast.  You would still have to make sure you have good coverage of a lot of zones.  Having 50 agents in 10 zones competing for the same business at different commission amounts could be a bad problem but you could overcome that with a standard percent.<br>
<br>
My original idea is probably too complicated and that is probably why no one else responded. So maybe we should start with your modification and go from there.<br>
<br>
Is anyone else interested? <br>
